Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /ˈuː.doː/, [ˈuː.d̪oː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /ˈu.do/, [ˈuː.d̪ɔ]

Etymology 1[edit]

Post-Classical. From ūdus.

Verb[edit]

ūdō (present infinitive ūdāre, perfect active ūdāvī); first conjugation, no supine stem

  1. I wet, moisten.

Descendants[edit]
  • Aromanian: ud, udari
  • Dalmatian: duot
  • Romanian: uda, udare

Etymology 2[edit]

From Ancient Greek οὐδών (oudṓn).

Noun[edit]

ūdō m (genitive ūdōnis); third declension

  1. A sock of felt or fur
Declension[edit]

Third-declension noun.
